<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06023175 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06023175 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Armed men with black kerchiefs covering their faces roused members of sixpeasant families early Tuesday in El Salvador, robbed them of their meagersavings and massacred 15 men and women. The victims were virtually the entireadult population of a cluster of bamboo-and-mud tin-roofed houses on a hillfive miles north of San Salvador, the capital. The mass killing was the worstin several years in the small Central American nation ravaged by 11 years ofcivil war against leftist guerrillas.;    According to soldiers' confessions,army troops massacred 10 peasants in central El Salvador in September 1988.Soldiers also massacred six Jesuit priests, their housekeeper and her daughterNov. 16, 1989. There was no immediate indication as to who committed Tuesday'sslayings, or if there was a political motive in addition to the motive ofrobbery.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MASKED BANDITS KILL 15 PEASANTS IN EL SALVADOR  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign News in Brief  </MEMO><TEXT>     Two children who survived Tuesday's raid said several men clad in blackclothing pounded on the doors of the peasant homes around midnight to demandmoney. They said that over the next hour or so the attackers ransacked thehouses and stabbed, slit the throats of, or shot seven men and eight women,the youngest of whom was 14.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910123  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  203  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday January 23, 199100023175,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>